Previous experiences has an abundent influence as to current decision making processes. Along with my father's and my uncle's military services, I would say that there were possibly two or three memorable experiences which led me to enter the service. The following probably had the greatest impact.<br><br>
This is not 'Nam specific but it had an impact on my role. When I was sixteen, I drank myself into a coma and was taken to Tripler Army hospital. While unconscious, a spinal tap was done that left me paralyzed from the waist down. Took me years to figure that it wasn't the drinking bout that caused the paralysis. Anyway, I stayed in the hospital for more than six months going through PT to regain the use of my legs. While there, I saw the first casualties come in from 'Nam. In no time the hospital filled and stayed that way for years. Tootin' around on a wheelchair gained me acess to all wards, with no restrictions. Played poker with double, triple amputees, talked story with burn cases, did therapy along side those learning to use their new prosthesis. I doubt that there was not a type of traumatic injured that<br>
I did not see. The worst were not the disfigured, but the head injured.<br><br>
When I left, as I suffered extreme pain, I was given access to as much darvon compound #65 as I wanted. Big tubs of them. The thinking was they were benign. All they were were ASA with a little speedball inside. But I got hooked on the darvons. Later they were taken off the market because of the addictive potential. I took them by the handfuls.<br><br>
When I went to basic, I left the darvons and the booze at home. I was one of those fuck-ups who couldn't run worth a shit, keep dropping out of formation during force marches. Many a nights, I laid awake lying in a fetal position, clutching my legs, suffering excruciating pain. Again,<br>
took years to realize I suffered from withdrawal symptons as well as problems with my legs. Needless to say, I didn't pass the final PT test. I was held back from graduating for two weeks. They didn't get another rotation of trainees for those two weeks, so three ADI's worked with me to strengthen my legs during the day. At night, they, being 'Nam vets,<br>
two injured, one lost half his foot while being extricated by chopper, shared their war experiences with me. I had received my orders for Ft.Sam, so they knew where I was headed, so they worked with me, telling me everything they could as to what I could expect as a medic. No bravado<br>
bullshit war stories, they were deeply concerned about how I did as a medic in the bush. After two tries, I finally passed the PT test by the skin of my teeth.<br><br>
I personally wouldn't mind hearing from others about experiences which drew them into the arm services thus 'Nam.<br><br>

